body:
Thank you for answer.
Still some comments:

Me wrote:

>> The same as declared the class members (inside a class name { }).

You answer me:

>> It's too easy to scroll away from the line func (*foo) and forget that you're looking at a method on *foo, not just a function Bar() bool.

My question.
Don't you think that: It's too easy to scroll away from the line `class ClassFoo` and forget that you're looking at a method on `ClassFoo`, not just a function `Bar()` bool ?

You answer me:

>> It's too easy to scroll away from the line func (*foo) and forget that you're looking at a method on *foo, not just a function Bar() bool.

My answer.
No. Because they will have different syntax.
Please compare (after formatting):

```go
// Function
func Foo() bool {
}

// Single method
func (f *foo) Foo() bool {
}

// Multiple methods
func (f *foo) (
  Foo() bool {
  }

  Baz() bool {
  }
)
```

The big diferrence is in that the "fun (* receiver)" are always ommited.
1. That is the judgement `forget that you're looking at a method on *foo, not just a function Bar() bool` is not true because each function starts with "func" but here we cannot see it.
2. Also, after formatting, each method start after some indentation because it are inside some `block` of identical declarations, and of course, as I can wrote below, member of parenthesized method declarations ommited redundant and repeated part which is `func *receiver`.
3. I don't propose the `parenthesized function declarations` in addition (because this is unnecessary since they don't have an owner), only methods with their owners can be (and should be for the better readabilty, siimilar to class members declarations) groupped and daclared inside a parenthesized declaration of `methods of the same receiver`.

P.S.
Sorry me, but I never think that inside a class declaration I can to forget abou that the I am inside a (so callled) `class body.` At least an different indentation level (of method, function beginning) says me that I am not inside a static function which always starts at the first column of the line.

And again, thank you very much for your (not always correct) explanations.
